rmk:
Extracted from a video taken by a zoo staff.
This bird was rescued on 2019 July 18.  It was a nestling still with
white feathers and was supposed to have fallen from the nest.
This bird was once released to the wild, but was captured again
since it didn't follow wild individuals on migration and transferred
to the zoo.

Details:
[https://www.pref.iwate.jp/_res/projects/default_project/_page_/001/005/490/sentertuushin14.pdf](https://www.pref.iwate.jp/_res/projects/default_project/_page_/001/005/490/sentertuushin14.pdf)

This voice was issued when the bird spontaneously on the body scale,
possibuly expecting for food (particularly honey) as a reward.

See
[https://twitter.com/moriokazoo/status/1444600613183049735](https://twitter.com/moriokazoo/status/1444600613183049735)

I uploaded it since second-year individuals are not considered to return
to the breeding ground and it is impossible to record the voice of
this age in the wild here.  This may also help identifying natural
vocalizations in the wintering ground.  The voice is somewhat
different (stronger and denser harmonics) from those by a more aged
captive bird in Himeji City Zoo (see  XC520214) and this may reflect
the difference in the age, or the reason of vocalization.

rmk:
Rattling call of Crested Honey Buzzard at nest.  The audio is
from the live streaming "Oriental Honey Buzzard Nest Cam"  (東方蜂鷹巢位直播)
presented by Raptor Research Group of Taiwan (台灣猛禽研究會)
at [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dq83GIow1OQ](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dq83GIow1OQ).

This audio was from [(7/1 猴群襲來) 東方蜂鷹巢位直播回顧 Oriental Honey Buzzard Nest Cam ハチクマの子育て生中継](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HMVmM4reJ94)
after permission from Raptor Research Group of Taiwan.

Please refer to [topic 44936](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/44936).
This type of call is known as rattling call or cycle-wheel call in
the European Honey Buzzard (Pernis apivorus), but has not been
documented in the Crested Honey Buzzard.
See [topic 32640](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/32640)
for the description of the rattling call in the European Honey Buzzard.

The chick and the female were at nest and a group of macaques 
passed near the nest causing aggression of the female bird.
The female issued the voice, erected the crest and later spread
the wing over the chick.
This recording corresponds to 5:18 of this video.

The audio is unmodified.  Apparent aliasing at 4 kHz.

rmk:
Voice from circling bird.  About on hour before, a mountain hawk-eagle
(Nisaetus nipalensis) visited the supposed nesting location
and the female bird issued calls of alarm, both perched and in flight
for nearly half an hour.  I am still uncertain about
the fate of the chicks of the this pair of the crested honey buzzard...
The mountain hawk-eagle departed and the female still continued
to call while perched on a different hill.
After the female's departure (apparently for foraging,
it returned with a filled crop about 1.5 hours later),
the male returned and calling while circling on the air.
This recording is a part of the later part of
the entire event.  The bird must have been very excited and the harmonics
were strongly present.
Water noise and equalization only.
See noise-reduced version XC487486.
The location is very approximate.

loc: Himeji City Zoo, Himeji City, Hyogo Prefecture
rmk:
Voice from a captive bird (this species/subspecies is native to Japan).
This bird was brought to this zoo in 2006 November.
The bird had been rescued and once release to the wild,
but was rescued again close to the released location.
The bird was then considered to be impossible to return to the wild
(the wing was somewhat damaged and couldn't fly for a long distance).

The bird started calling after I took a lunch in front of the bird.
The bird probably wished to eat.  I share this recording since
this type of vocalization would be very difficult to obtain
in the wild, and since the voice is different from (but has some similarity with)
the begging call of the European Honey Buzzard (cf. XC500777,
see [forum topic 30888](https://www.xeno-canto.org/forum/topic/30888).
Silent parts were cut (the intervals between calls were typically 10s).
The time sequence of the entire event was in reverse chronological
order in XC numbers (i.e. starting from XC520219 and ending
with XC520214).
To my knowledge, this is one of only three facilities in Japan where
captive Crested Honey Buzzards are presented to the public.

Yet another individual of this species in a zoo in Morioka,
newly presented to the public in 2020:
[https://twitter.com/moriokazoo/status/1195527023776526336](https://twitter.com/moriokazoo/status/1195527023776526336) (with voice).

[https://twitter.com/moriokazoo/status/1339409492627222531](https://twitter.com/moriokazoo/status/1339409492627222531) (with voice of excitement looking at comb honey).

For information about the vocabulary of this species
(of a rescued bird), there is a video:
[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r-r6R6QrgBg](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r-r6R6QrgBg).
Rattling call is heard at 1:08 of this video.
Other call (which I'm not familiar with) at 0:29.

More very interesting videos of captive individuals
in Korea (with voice):
[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ijiylo8WVss](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ijiylo8WVss),
[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y_SuOnGZ2XI](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y_SuOnGZ2XI).
The voice sounds similar to the ones
I have recorded.

Video [The Oriental Honey Buzzard of Ninety-nine Peaks](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UyZRkr0puI4).  Starting at 7:26, 41:17 of this film (particularly at 41:30),
the same type of voice in zoos is issued when the birds gathered in an apiary.
This voice appears to be contact call between nearby individuals.

Suppressed voice of a wild individual [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=24FfqcGDMGQ](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=24FfqcGDMGQ).

See also [Created Honey Buzzard call](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GbmxHo19Hr4),
which gave the same type of vocalization recorded in captivity (XC678958).
This illustrates the importance of recorded vocalizations in captivity
as a reference to study the communication in wild individual.
